    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="1219"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1219">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2729.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of War</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">War Department</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 3, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Colonel Edgar Z. Steever, Fourth Cavalry, commanding Fort Bliss, Texas, sends the
                    following: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Mexican authorities in Juárez, also Mexican consul in El Paso, notified
                            to prevent any firing into United States territory in case of further
                            disturbances or disorder in or about Juárez, The Governor of Texas has
                            sent similar message to military commander in Juárez in connection with
                            my notification, and invite [sic] attention to the fact that last spring
                            similar warnings were sent to General Navarro, the Federal commander,
                            and General Madero, the insurrectionary chief. However, this warning did
                            not prevent numerous shots falling upon United States territory, killing
                            and wounding in El Paso some twenty-five persons. In case of bullets or
                            other projectiles falling upon United States territory in spite of my
                            warnings, what further action, if any, does the Secretary of War desire
                            me to take?</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">H. L. Stimson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
